metadata.name: Cosmic Type #324
metadata.description:
Cosmic Type is a kinetic type experiment that explores both graphic space as structural and semantic agency. Inspired by the early pioneering work of the concrete poets such as Dom Sylvester Hou√©dard, Ian Hamilton Finley and Steve McCaffe, the project is a play with letters, words and graphic form in the computational and generative space.

Each iteration gives you the possibility to discover a variety of visual form through exploring the system. Please explore your iteration with the key interactions below. It is hoped that you give the time to explore and observe. If you don't, you may end up with just a blank canvas. 

Thank you for collecting. 

Key Interactions

metadata.name: tr4ns4ctions #25
metadata.description:
Tr4ns4ctions is a series of real-time animations that use pixels to create an abstraction of the movement of values. The pixels are constantly rearranging, being transferred from offer to taker, liquify, appear and disappear. They are forming endless compositions, sometimes intransparent or with strange spins.

The level of abstraction has been set to a 2x pixel size and the color palette of the NES with 12 different color modes. 16 pixel patterns serve as the fundamental building blocks and a simplex noise field determines the direction of movement.

click || space => pause/unpause

View all tr4ns4ctions at https://tr4ns4ctions.com

Kim Asendorf, 2022

metadata.name: Momentary #203
metadata.description:
Sometimes, life's troubles seem to be immense and endless. They make us run around in despair, helplessly looking in every direction in search of an answer.

It's tough to be in control of those situations until we understand that everything in our life is momentary, the good times are momentary and of course the bad ones.

We tend to forget that life finds its way and that we just need to hold enough to start to see a clear path to follow.

Life is momentary, the good times are momentary and of course the bad ones.

Hold enough.

There is a path to follow.

metadata.name: One Eleven (are Better Than Thirty) #56
metadata.description:
One Eleven (are Better Than Thirty), is the fourth installment of One Eleven, a periodical experiment.

Even though Andy Warhols work is not cc0, the Mona Lisa is. So yes, this is inspired, heavily, by Andy Warhol, most notably the piece Thirty are Better Than One, but uses no component of it. Let‚Äôs call it an homage. We also feel that if Andy were alive today, they would embrace cc0. Art is just about fame and exposure anyways, right?

And yes, initially we wanted to make a grid that had exactly 111 Mona Lisas on it, but tbh, it looked terrible. They were too small, and the iterations were too same-y. So, instead, each iteration of this will have 111 pages, each with varying amounts of Mona Lisas. You just click the art and a new page appears. 111 for each one minted. Then it loops back around.

So, really, this collection gives you 111 pieces for the price of 1, which is free. Pretty good deal.

How do you get on the list? Read below:

Collectors of the genesis One Eleven (#12743) are on the allow list for all One Eleven collections, this one included. A bit before minting is enabled, the list will be updated granting one reserve for each iteration held. So, buy one before this drops. Any procured after the scheduled release time will not get you on the list, but will be considered once the reserves are lifted. Reserves will be lifted after 111 hours, give or take.

As a bonus, whoever holds One Eleven #1 will receive #1 of this collection as an airdrop. The project will be disabled until that happens, but should occur right around the scheduled time.

Half of the royalties for all One Eleven collections will be shared with the minter.

This collection uses the One Eleven SDK, which makes embedding One Eleven into FXHash collections very simple. You can use it if you like for your projects, as it is cc0. Talk to us on twitter if you'd like to release it as a collab.

More info: an0n.wtf/sdk

I'm sorry this is so complicated. When it started, it seemed simpler.

metadata.name: A Clock #193
metadata.description:
This generative token is based on a project I originally coded in late 2014, possibly my first creative project in JavaScript during graduate school at NYU ITP, which has run here since then: https://rossgoodwin.com/clock

The text in this case is not generated, but rather (legally) snipped from public domain e-books on Project Gutenberg (https://gutenberg.org/), and recontextualized as a real-time clock.

The editions vary in color palette and font choice, each with unique text for every minute determined by the clock's unique hash. For nearly all word/phrase blocks in the template system, there exist 512 possible excerpts you could receive, and countless possible combinations thereof. Additionally, 16 possible color palettes, 8 possible fonts, and many bezel types will determine your clock's visual appearance.

Unlike my original 2014 iteration, I wrote this clock in Vanilla JS with zero dependencies. (Largely, that's thanks to eight additional years of programming experience.) As a result, it's faster (once loaded) and more responsive as well.
